# Empty intersection operands (`Record<string, never>`)

When a conditional type needs an **empty** piece to intersect (e.g. "omit this field from the context"), do **not** use `Record<string, never>` as the neutral operand.

## Why

`Record<string, never>` is `{ [key: string]: never }` — it carries a **string index signature**. Intersecting it with an interface propagates that index signature to the whole type:

- `string extends keyof T` becomes **true**
- Any property access (`ctx.args`, `ctx.state`, …) typechecks even when the field was intentionally omitted
- `@ts-expect-error` and `keyof` regression asserts silently fail (unused directive / false negatives)

## Use instead

```ts
// Empty part for intersection — no string index signature
type EmptyPart = Record<never, never>;

type WithOptionalField<TSchema> =
  HasField<TSchema> extends true
    ? { readonly field: InferOutput<TSchema> }
    : EmptyPart;

type Context = CoreContext & WithOptionalField<TArgsSchema>;
```

Avoid `{}` in this repo if `@typescript-eslint/no-empty-object-type` applies — prefer `Record<never, never>` or a small named alias at the call site.

## Regression signal

If `@ts-expect-error void ctx.someRemovedField` becomes **unused** while the field should be absent, check whether a recent conditional branch introduced `Record<string, never>` into an intersection chain.
